It gives the false impression that A: the charger is literally free(which it isn't) and B: that the charger is not free, but the ppl who get the box without the chargers are paying the same as those getting the charger. Honestly, I think that just adding some negligible number to the price of the charger included box, like 5 to 10 dollars, it would virtually eliminate all those false illusions and possible misunderstandings about the value of the charger.

I want to see the next step in folding screens, whether it's better scratch resistance, smaller creases or even different ways to fold it.

On the other end, I'm glad to see cheap phones becoming every bit as good as older flagships. Just 10 years ago, a bottom end Android phone was not much more than a phone with a touch screen, put a few apps on it and it slows down to unbelievable slow, practically unusable levels, now people on a budget are afforded the ability to have a phone with a good amount of RAM, a decent enough amount of storage to get by before using an SD card, actually good screens, so I'm also excited to see how good a cheap phone can get, how cheap a phone I can actually recommend can become, maybe even a folding phone at a reasonable price with decent enough specs to make them the new flip phones like we used to see in the 2000s

Here's my take on the no charger included with your new phone, that apparently became the "standard" overnight..

I absolutely fucin hate it! And as most of us have figured out by now, it's OBVIOUSLY only about saving money and earning quite a bit extra on top of that for these tech giants, the environment actually will suffer from this.

But other than that, why do I hate it? Well..

1. People switch between different brands, most (as far as I can tell) don't stay with one brand for 10 years, apart from apple sheep's, but they still get sacked by dear, dear T.Crocked leader. And when you change brand the new phone doesn't necessarily work with the new charger even though both phones have USB-C connectors. Also the old charger is probably charging at 5-10 W so you'd like an upgrade regardless.

2. What about new costumers Apple, Samsung and the rest, huh?! You do realize new people are born everyday right..? And that these people are going to buy their first phones one day. And that day is right now, because previously born are in their teens now or in their three's or five's 😂 coz that's apparently when you get your first phone these days for a lot of middle class and above western kids at least.

3. Here's an interesting fact.. Yes, you can sorta buy one USB-C charger for everything now, if it's of the right type and power output, though many laptops still use and/or require a proprietary charger. However, maybe I don't want to charge everything at the maximum rate, or let's say that I am a person that once every year or more often, manage to leave behind a charger in a hotel room, because I was stressed to make it to the airport on time. Maybe I'll be pretty fucin screwed if I don't have an extra! So guess what? I always buy at least one extra charger to every phone I buy. That means that I have to buy at least two chargers now with every new phone, and they ain't exactly super cheap. So I'd say.. one charger in the box isn't even something to be questioned. And an extra at almost no cost, should be offered with a new phone purchase. Not only for the mentioned "leave it behind" case above, but simply for convenience. Like having one at your workplace for example, or at your getaway summer cabin. Or perhaps just having one in a different room.

My own experience with a previous version of Xiaomi phone is that it has an amazing display, good performance and a very reasonably priced phone BUT...
There seems to be lots of security issues in the phone, I usually keep my location off and browse the internet incognito. Once I was using my Xiaomi phone I noticed that the default browser was showing my accurate location, surprised, I checked and rechecked my setting for location to be 'Off' but indeed it still shows my accurate location. I tried to turn it off and restart and then tried to move a few hundred meters away - and there- it accurately updated my live location. So Xiaomi secretly tracks me even if I switched off the location setting.
Not just that, I love the concept of running my Android apps in a least permission sandbox and was surprised to find that many of the default Xiaomi apps have unnecessary permission requirements. I checked it only (I commute an hour everyday so lots of spare time :) to find that there are plenty of other users complaining about the same issue and surprisingly the developers of Xiaomi are shockingly rude in their replies in public online forums!
I ditched my perfectly good Xiaomi phone and bought an iPhone and changed all my passwords. Nothing is worth more for me than my privacy.

Beautify mode is ruining the quality of the image on both front and back, despite the increase in megapixels. As a man was passing the elephants, he suddenly stopped, confused by the fact that these huge creatures were being held by only a small rope tied to their front leg. No chains, no cages. It was obvious that the elephants could, at anytime, break away from their bonds but for some reason, they did not.
He saw a trainer nearby and asked why these animals just stood there and made no attempt to get away. “Well,” trainer said, “when they are very young and much smaller we use the same size rope to tie them and, at that age, it’s enough to hold them. As they grow up, they are conditioned to believe they cannot break away. They believe the rope can still hold them, so they never try to break free.”
The man was amazed. These animals could at any time break free from their bonds but because they believed they couldn’t, they were stuck right where they were.
Like the elephants, how many of us go through life hanging onto a belief that we cannot do something, simply because we failed at it once before?
Failure is part of learning; we should never give up the struggle in life.
